This does not just confirm that at least some dinosaurs had feathers, which is already a widespread theory, but also provides details that fossils cannot give, such as color or three-dimensional arrangement.
Scientists say that the plumage of this animal was chestnut-brown with pale or carotenoid-colored lower edges.
The discovery also gives understanding about the evolution of feathers in birds.
Since the dinosaur feathers do not have a well-developed quill, called rachis, but do have other characteristics of feathers – branches and twigs – the researchers concluded that the rachis is probably a later evolutionary achievement than those other characteristics.
According to the structure of the feathers, it is assumed that they were not used for flight, but more likely for thermoregulation or display. The researchers conjectured that the specimen shows a fully grown plumage and not juvenile down, although it is a tail of a young dinosaur.
The researchers speculated that the specimen shows a fully grown feather quill and not down, although it is about the tail of a young dinosaur.
