In France, voting was traditionally a simple experience: voters isolate themselves in a booth, place a pre-printed ballot paper with the indication of their preferred candidate in an envelope.
After officials confirm the voter's identity, the voter inserts the ballot into the ballot box and signs the voting list.
French voting law sufficiently strictly codifies the procedure.
Since 1988, polling stations must be transparent, so that voters and observers can attest that there are no envelopes before the start of the voting and that no envelopes are added except those of the duly calculated and authorized voters.
Candidates can send representatives to testify every phase of the process. In the evening volunteers count the votes under attentive control, according to specific procedures.
