When a small group of living beings (a small population) separates from the main population, from which it originates (like when they cross a mountain or a river, or when they migrate to a new island, so that they cannot easily return), they often find themselves in a medium different from that where they were before.
This new medium has other resources and other competitors, so the new population must, in order to be a strong competitor, have other traits or adaptations compared to those it needed before.
The original population has not changed at all, they still need the same adaptations as before.
As time passes, as the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, it begins to look less and less like the other population.
Fine, after passage of thousands or even millions of years, the two populations will look so different that they cannot be called the same species.
We call this process speciation, which simply means the formation of new species. Speciation is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
