Civilization is a separate culture shared by a significantly large group of people who live and work together, society.
The word civilization comes from the Latin civilis, which means civil, related to the Latin civis, citizen, and civitas, which means city or city-state, and also defines the dimension of society.
City-states are predecessors of nations. Cultural civilization subsumes the transmission of knowledge through several generations, a lasting cultural heritage and quite a large dissemination.
Smaller cultures often disappear without leaving relevant historical evidence and fail to be recognized as suitable civilizations.
During the revolutionary war, the thirteen states first formed a weak central government – with Congress as its sole component – under the Articles of Confederation.
At the Congress lacked any power to collect taxes and, since there was no national executive or judiciary, it entrusted the implementation of its decisions to the institutions of the states, which often were not cooperative.
It also did not have the right to rule over tax laws and tariffs between states.
The Articles demanded the unanimous consent of all states before any change, and states related to the central government so easily, that their representatives often absented themselves.
