In 1624 the Dutch East India Company founded a base in south-western Taiwan, transforming the indigenous methods of rice and sugar production and employing Chinese workers to work in their rice and sugar plantations.
In 1683 troops of the Qing dynasty (1644-1912) occupied the western and northern coastal areas of Taiwan and declared Taiwan a province of the Qing Empire in 1885.
In 1895, after the defeat in the First Sino-Japanese War (1894-1895), the Qing government signed the Treaty of Shimonoseki, under which it ceded sovereignty over Taiwan to Japan, which ruled the island until 1945.
