For example, the most common format in the world for taking still images is 35 mm, which was the dominant film dimension at the end of the analog film era.
It is still produced today, but what is more important, its proportion has been inherited from the sensor formats of digital cameras.
The 35 mm format is actually, somewhat confusingly, 36 mm wide and 34 mm high.
The ratio of this format (divided by twelve to receive the simplest integer ratio) is therefore called 3:2.
Many popular formats (such as the APS format) are equal to or very close to this proportion.
