Before the Middle Ages was the Early Middle Ages and it was followed by the Late Middle Ages, which ends around 1500 by agreement.
Technological determinism is a term that practically covers a wide range of ideas, from technological push or the technological imperative to a strict sense that human destiny is driven by underlying logic linked to scientific laws and their manifestation in technology.
Most interpreters of technological determinism share two general ideas: that the development of technology itself largely follows a path independent of cultural or political influences, and that technology in turn has "consequences" essentially its own, and not socially conditioned.
For example, one could say that the automobile necessarily leads to the development of roads.
However, a nationwide network is not economically feasible for just a few cars, so new production methods are designed to reduce the costs of car ownership.
Mass car ownership also leads to a higher incidence of accidents on the road, which leads to the invention of new medical techniques to repair damaged bodies.
Romanticism had a great element of cultural determinism, taken by writers like Goethe, Fichte and Schlegel.
In the context of romanticism, geography moulded individuals and with the passage of time customs and culture related to that geography emerged, and those, more harmonious with the place of the society, were better than arbitrarily imposed laws.
Just as Paris is known as the fashion capital of the modern world, so Constantinople was considered the fashion capital of feudal Europe.
Its reputation as a center of luxury began around 400 BC and lasted until around 1100 BC.
In the 12th century its status degenerated mainly because the Crusaders returned with silks and spices considered more valuable than those offered by the Byzantine markets.
It was at that time, that the title Fashion Capital was transferred from Constantinople to Paris.
Gothic style reached its peak in the period between the 10th—11th centuries and the 14th century.
In the beginning, clothing was greatly influenced by Byzantine culture in the East.
However, due to slow communication tools, styles in the West could lag behind by 25 to 30 years.
At the end of the Middle Ages, Western Europe began to develop its own style. One of the major achievements of the period was that people started using buttons to fasten clothing as a result of the Crusades.
Sustainable agriculture is farming done to produce enough food for the needs only of the farmer and his/her family.
Sustainable agriculture is simple, often organic, a system using saved indigenous seeds for the bioregion with crop rotation or other relatively simple techniques to increase harvest.
Most of the terracotta cultists were involved in subsistence agriculture and that still holds true in many developing states.
Subcultures unite people with similar viewpoints, who feel marginalized by social norms, and allow them to grow a sense of identity.
Subcultures can be distinguished by age, ethnic affiliation, class, location, and/or gender of the members.
The determining factors for a subculture as a separate one, can be linguistic, aesthetic, religious, political, sexual, geographical or a combination of factors.
Subcultural members often signify their membership by recognizable and symbolic use of style, which includes fashion, attitude and slang.
One of the most common methods used to illustrate the importance of socialization is to mention a few unfortunate cases of children who, due to neglect, bad luck, or malicious mistreatment, were not socialized by adults.
Such children are called "feral" or feral. Some feral children were captured by humans (usually their own parents); in some cases such a rejection of a child was due to the refusal of a serious intellectual or physical disability of a child by the parents.
Feral children could survive a harsh ordeal or trauma before being abandoned or fleeing.
Some were said to have been grown by animals; some were said to have lived in nature independently.
Raised only by wild animals, the feral child shows behaviors (within physical limitations) almost entirely similar to those of a certain caring animal, as well as its fear or indifference towards humans.
