The internet unites elements of both mass and interpersonal communication.
The special features of the Internet give additional dimensions to the theory of uses and rewards.
For example, "learning" and "socializing" are suggested as important reasons to use the Internet (James et al., 1995).
Eighmey and McCord (1998) also identified "personal involvement" and "ongoing relationships" as new motivating factors, when they investigated responses of the public to websites.
