Research in the 20th century showed that there are two groups of genetic variation: hidden and represented.
Mutation adds a new gene variation, and selection removes it from the group of visible variation.
Recombination and recombination remixes the variation back and forth between the two groups in each generation.
In the savannah it is difficult for a primate with a digestive system like that of humans to satisfy their needs for amino acids from available plants.
In addition, failure to do this has serious consequences: reduction in growth, malnutrition, and finally death.
The most easily accessible resources of plants would be proteins obtainable from leaves and beans, but those are difficult to digest for primates like us, unless they are cooked.
Male, animal-derived foods (insects, termites, eggs) are not only easily digestible, but also provide high-quality proteins, which contain the essential amino acids.
Considering all circumstances, we should not be surprised if our ancestors solved their "protein problem" in a similar way as chimpanzees do in the savannah today.
Sleep inertia is the process of intentional awakening during your regular sleep period and falling asleep again after a short time (10–60 minutes).
You can do this by using a relatively gentle alarm clock to wake up without fully waking up.
If you notice, you are rewinding the clock while you are sleeping, it can be left on the other side of the room, which will cause you to get up to turn it off.
Among other options based on bio-rhythms is to drink a lot of liquid (especially water or tea, a known diuretic) before sleep, which would make you urinate.
The extent of internal peace that a person has, negatively correlates with the extent of tension in the body and spirit.
The lower the tension, the more positive force is in life. Every person has the potential to find absolute peace and contentment.
Everyone can achieve illumination. The only obstacle on the way to that goal is your own tension and negativism.
The Tibetan Buddhism is based on the teachings of Buddha, but was expanded by the Mahayana way of love and by many techniques from Indian yoga.
The Tibetan Buddhism is very simple. It consists of tantric yoga, meditation and the path of universal love.
In Kundalini yoga, the Kundalini energy (energy of illumination) is awakened by yogic postures, breath control, mantras, and visualizations.
In the center of Tibetan meditation is the daily practice. By visualizing various deities, one purifies the energetic channels, activates the chakras, and creates the illuminated consciousness.
