Using ships for the transportation of goods is the most effective way to move large quantities of people and goods across oceans.
The work of the navy traditionally was to ensure that your country could move your people and goods, while at the same time preventing your enemy from moving their people and goods.
One of the most notable recent examples is the North Atlantic campaign of the Second World War. Americans tried to move people and materials across the Atlantic Ocean to help Britain.
At the same time, the German navy, mainly using U-boats, tried to stop this traffic.
If the allies failed, Germany would probably be able to conquer Britain as well as the rest of Europe.
Goats were seemingly domesticated for the first time approximately 10,000 years ago in the Zagros Mountains in Iran.
Ancient cultures and tribes domesticated them for easy access to milk, wool, meat, and hides.
Domesticated goats were generally kept in herds roaming on hills and other pastures, often taken care of by shepherds, who were often children or adolescents, similar to the more widely known shepherd. Those breeding methods are still used today.
Railways were constructed in England no earlier than the 16th century.
Although railroads consisted of simple parallel wooden planks, they allowed the horses pulling them to reach greater speeds and pull heavier loads than on the slightly smoother roads of that time.
Railway sleepers appeared early enough to hold the tracks in place. However, it soon became clear that the tracks would be more effective if they had an iron rail on top.
This became a popular practice, but iron caused a faster wear of wooden wheels of the wagons.
They were then replaced by iron rails. In 1767 the first entirely iron rails were presented.
The earliest known mode of transportation was walking, people began to go vertically about two million years ago with the appearance of Homo Erectus (meaning upright man).
Their ancestors, australopithecines, did not walk upright as often.
Bipedalismo is found in the fossils of australopithecines dating back 4.2-3.9 million years ago, although Sahelanthropus probably walked on two legs as early as seven million years ago.
