The modern city of Casablanca was founded by Berber fishermen in the 10th century BC, and was used by Phoenicians, Romans, and Vandals as a strategic port called Anfa.
Destroyed by the Portuguese, it was rebuilt by them with the name Casa Branca, but they left after the earthquake in 1755.
The city was rebuilt by the Sultan of Morocco under the name Daru l-Badya and the Spanish merchants, who set up shops there, called it Casablanca.
As for shopping, Casablanca is one of the least interesting places in Morocco.
Around the old city center, it's easy to find shops selling traditional Moroccan goods, such as souvenirs, ceramics, leather goods, nargilehs and a whole range of glittering things, but everything is for tourists.
Goma is a tourist town in the Democratic Republic of the Congo in the extreme east near Rwanda.
In 2002 the volcano Nyiragongo destroyed Goma, covering most of the urban street with its lava, especially in the city center.
Rubber offers sufficient security, but you have to inform yourself about each visit outside of it in order to know the state of the ongoing battles in the province of North Kivu.
The city is also the base to climb the volcano Nyiragongo in addition to the cheapest trekking of mountain gorillas in Africa.
You can use the boda-boda (motorcycle taxi) to travel through Goma. The normal (local) price is about 500 Congolese francs for the short trip.
In addition to its relative inaccessibility, "Timbuktu" was used as a metaphor for exotic and distant lands.
Today Timbuktu is a poverty-stricken town, but it is a tourist attraction due to its reputation and it has an airport.
In 1990 it was inscribed in the red list of world heritage due to the threatening sands from the desert.
It was one of the main stops during the special PBS program Wonders of the African World by Henry Louis Gates.
The city is very different from the other cities in the country, as it has a style more Arab than African.
The Kruger National Park (KNP) is in northeastern South Africa and runs east along the border with Mozambique, north to Zimbabwe and south to the Crocodile River.
The park covers 19,500 km² and is divided into 14 separate ecoregions, each of which supports a unique fauna.
It presents one of the main attractions in South Africa and is considered as the most symbolic among the South African National Parks (SANParks).
Like all South African National Parks, there are day entry fees for the park.
It's also useful to buy a Wild Card, which provides access, whether to selected parks in South Africa or to all South African National Parks.
The Hong Kong Island gives its name to the territory of Hong Kong and it is the place that many tourists consider the most interesting.
The line of buildings that creates the Hong Kong skyline was compared to a shining histogram that is visible due to the presence of the waters of Victoria Harbour.
To get the best views of Hong Kong, leave the island and cross over to the front, which is located on the waterfront of Kowloon.
Most of the urban growth of the Hong Kong Island is densely concentrated on land that was won from the sea at the northern coastline.
This is the place which the British colonizers annexed to themselves, and therefore, if one is looking for a proof of the colonial past of the territory, here is an opportune place to search.
The Sundarbans is the world's largest mangrove forest, stretching 80 km (50 miles) along the coast into Bangladesh and India.
The Sundarbans was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The part of the forest in the Indian territory is called Sundarbans National Park.
The forest, however, is not just a mangrove swamp. In it are some of the last refuges of the impressive jungles that once covered the low-lying plain.
The Sundarbans covers an area of 3,850 km², of which approximately one-third is covered by water or marshes.
In 1966 Sundarbans became a reserve and it is estimated that there are currently 400 Bengal tigers and around 30,000 spotted deer on its territory.
Buses depart from the inter-district bus station (across the river) throughout the day, but the majority depart between 6:30 and 7:30, especially those traveling west and to Jakar or Bumthang.
Since intercity buses are often crowded, it is advisable to buy a ticket a few days in advance.
Most of the districts are linked by small Japanese Coaster buses, which are comfortable and strong.
Public buses are fast and comfortable vehicles for traveling to nearby places, like Paro (150 Nu) and Punakha (200 Nu).
The Oyapock River Bridge is a railway bridge. It spans the Oyapock River, connecting the towns of Oiapoque in Brazil and Saint-Georges-de-l’Oyapock in French Guiana.
The two towers are 83 meters high, it is 378 meters wide and it has two corridors 3.50 m wide.
The vertical distance below the bridge is 15 meters. The construction was completed in August 2011, but it did not open to traffic until March 2017.
Plans are to have the bridge fully operational in September 2017, when the Brazilian customs crossings are expected to be completed.
The Guarani were the most notable indigenous group living in that place, which is now eastern Paraguay, living like semi-nomadic hunters, who also practiced subsistence agriculture.
The Chaco region was inhabited by other groups of indigenous tribes, such as the Guaycurú and Payaguá, who lived by hunting, gathering and fishing.
In the 16th century, Paraguay, previously known as "The Great Province of Indians", was formed as a result of the encounter of Spanish conquerors and the indigenous groups.
The Spaniards began an era of colonization, which lasted for three centuries.
Since Asunción was founded in 1537, Paraguay has succeeded in retaining a lot of its indigenous character and identity.
