The official currency of the Falkland Islands is the Falkland pound (FKP), the value of which has been pegged to that of the British pound (GBP).
The money is exchangeable in the single bank on the islands, which is located in front of the FIC West shop in Stanley.
Everywhere on the islands, British pounds are generally accepted, and in Stanley, credit cards and US dollars are often accepted as well.
On will probably not accept credit cards on the outer islands, but you can take British and US money; ask in advance to know which payment method is accepted.
Because it's almost impossible to change a Falkland Islands pound outside the islands, change your money before leaving.
Because Montevideo is located south of the equator, it has summer when in the northern hemisphere it is winter, and vice versa.
Montevideo is in the subtropics; in the summer months, the temperature usually exceeds 30 °C.
Winter can be deceptively cold: the temperature rarely becomes frosty, but the wind and humidity combine and therefore one feels colder than what the thermometer indicates.
There are no separate "rainy" and "dry" seasons: the rainfall is almost the same throughout the year.
Although many of the park's animals have grown accustomed to the presence of humans, the animals are still wild and should not be fed or bothered.
The park authorities request that you stay at least 100 yards/meters away from bears and wolves, and 25 yards/meters away from all other wild animals!
No matter how peaceful they may appear, bears, boars, deer, bears and almost all animals can attack.
Dozens of visitors are injured every year, because they are not keeping an adequate distance. Because these animals are large, wild, and potentially dangerous, keep their space.
Besides, be aware that scents attract bears and other wildlife, and therefore avoid carrying or cooking aromatic foods and keep the campsite clean.
The city of Apia, the capital of Samoa, is located on the island of Upolu and in it live only a little less than 40,000 people.
Apia was founded in the 1850s and it became the capital of Samoa in 1959.
The harbour was the site of the famous naval confrontation in 1889, when seven ships from Germany, the United States, and Britain refused to leave the harbour.
All ships were sunk, except for one British cruiser. About 200 Americans and Germans lost their lives.
In the struggle for independence, organized by the Mau movement, a peaceful gathering in the city led to the death of the paramount chief Tupua Tamasese Lealofi III.
Auckland has many beaches thanks to its location between two harbours. The most popular ones are in three regions.
The beaches of North Shore (in the North Haven district) are at the Pacific and extend from Long Bay in the north to Devonport in the south.
Almost all have sandy beaches where you can safely swim, and most have a canopy of palm trees.
The beaches of Tamaki Drive are at the Waitemata Harbour in the affluent suburbs of Mission Bay and Saint Heliers in Central Auckland.
They are sometimes completely crowded family beaches where shops abound along the shore. Swimming is safe.
The main local beer is Number One. It is not a complex beer, but it is tasty and refreshing. The other local beer is called Manta.
There are many fine wines from France, but wines from New Zealand and Australia may turn out better.
It is perfectly safe to drink the well water, but bottled water is easily available if you have concerns.
