Japanese work culture is more hierarchical and formal than one to which Westerners may be accustomed.
Uniforms are the normal working clothes and coworkers address each other with family names or job titles.
Teamwork is the most important, just like the emphasis on group effort instead of praising individual achievements.
Employees usually have to receive the approval of their superiors for all made decisions and they have to obey the instructions unconditionally.
